# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram
In [25]:
def labelled_barplot(data, column, figsize=(12, 6), title=None, label_fontsize=10, label_offset=0.02):
    """
    Function to create a labeled bar plot for categorical variables, with adjustments to handle overlap and font size.

    Parameters:
    - data: pandas DataFrame
    - column: str, the name of the categorical column to plot
    - figsize: tuple, the size of the figure (default is (12, 6))
    - title: str, the title of the plot (default is None)
    - label_fontsize: int, the font size of the labels (default is 10)
    - label_offset: float, the offset for the label position, will be adjusted based on max height (default is 0.02)
    """

    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)

    # Create barplot
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=column, palette='viridis')

    # Calculate label offset based on the maximum count (height)
    max_height = max([p.get_height() for p in ax.patches])
    label_offset = max_height * label_offset
    
    # Add labels to the bars with 90-degree rotation
    for p in ax.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        ax.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2.,
                height + label_offset,
                f'{int(height)}', 
                ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=label_fontsize )

    # Title and labels
    if title:
        plt.title(title, fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel(column, fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=12)
    
    # Show plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

## Function to plot distributions


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model Building

**Model evaluation criterion** The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows: 1.True positives (TP) are defaults correctly predicted by the model. 2.False negatives (FN) are real loan defaults where there is no detection by model. 3.False positives (FP) are loan defaults detections where there is no default. ##Which metric to measure? 1.Our score is the percentage of all correct predictions made. This is simply known as accuracy. 2.The best accuracy is 1 whereas the worst is 0. 3.It will be calculated as the total number of two correct predictions (True positive + True negative) divided by the total number of observations in the dataset.

Define models to test on orginal data

model = XGBClassifier(random_state=42, eval_metric='logloss')

# Parameter grid to pass in GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    'scale_pos_weight': [5, 10],
    'gamma': [0, 3, 5],
    'subsample': [0.8, 0.9],
    'n_estimators': [150,200,250],
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.2],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = make_scorer(accuracy_score)

# Calling GridSearchCV
grid_cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, scoring=scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

grid_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best Parameters: {}\nScore: {}".format(grid_cv.best_params_, grid_cv.best_score_))

RandomizedSearch is faster than GridSearch with execution time of 3min 49s and 4min 39s respectively, but both have the same recall score.1.The initial XGBoost model's accuracy was 87.15%, meaning the model correctly identified 87.15% of all instances (both positive and negative) in the validation set. That is, it correctly predicted the class label for 87.15% of all instances in the validation set. 2.After tuning the hyperparameters using GridSearchC and RandomizedSearchV, both achieved an average cross-validated accuracy score of approximately 84.96% which performed lower than the accuracy of the original data. 3. We will still go ahead with XGBoost for fimal model.

We know that we can use pipelines to standardize the model building, but the steps in a pipeline are applied to each and every variable. 2.We use Column Transformer to personalize the pipeline to perform different preprocessing steps on different column 3.Using pipeline models is a best practice in designing machine learning workflows. They help ensure consistency, reduce errors, and streamline experimentation and deployment processes, making machine learning projects more robust, maintainable, and scalable.s.
